87: /**
88:  * Internal {@link Processor} that Camel routing engine used during routing for cross cutting functionality such as:
89:  * <ul>
90:  * <li>Execute {@link UnitOfWork}</li>
91:  * <li>Keeping track which route currently is being routed</li>
92:  * <li>Execute {@link RoutePolicy}</li>
93:  * <li>Gather JMX performance statics</li>
94:  * <li>Tracing</li>
95:  * <li>Debugging</li>
96:  * <li>Message History</li>
97:  * <li>Stream Caching</li>
98:  * <li>{@link Transformer}</li>
99:  * </ul>
100:  * ... and more.
101:  * <p/>
102:  * This implementation executes this cross cutting functionality as a {@link CamelInternalProcessorAdvice} advice
103:  * (before and after advice) by executing the {@link CamelInternalProcessorAdvice#before(org.apache.camel.Exchange)} and
104:  * {@link CamelInternalProcessorAdvice#after(org.apache.camel.Exchange, Object)} callbacks in correct order during
105:  * routing. This reduces number of stack frames needed during routing, and reduce the number of lines in stacktraces, as
106:  * well makes debugging the routing engine easier for end users.
107:  * <p/>
108:  * <b>Debugging tips:</b> Camel end users whom want to debug their Camel applications with the Camel source code, then
109:  * make sure to read the source code of this class about the debugging tips, which you can find in the
110:  * {@link #process(org.apache.camel.Exchange, org.apache.camel.AsyncCallback)} method.
111:  * <p/>
112:  * The added advices can implement {@link Ordered} to control in which order the advices are executed.
113:  */
